menu "breadboard: bb_bqueue"

config BB_BQUEUE_MAX_INSTANCES
    int "Maximum concurrent bb_bqueue instances"
    default 2
    help
        Size of the static instance pool bb_bqueue_create() allocates from.
        TaipanMiner needs exactly two: a work queue and a result queue.
        Zero heap: every instance lives in this fixed-size pool.
        bb_bqueue_create() returns BB_ERR_NO_SPACE once it is exhausted.

        SRAM cost: every instance in the pool reserves
        BB_BQUEUE_MAX_CAPACITY * BB_BQUEUE_MAX_ITEM_BYTES bytes of static
        item storage regardless of that instance's actual cfg (see those
        options' help text) -- raising this value multiplies that
        per-instance cost by the new instance count, even for callers that
        only ever create one small queue.

config BB_BQUEUE_MAX_CAPACITY
    int "Maximum queue capacity (items) per instance"
    default 16
    help
        Upper bound on cfg->capacity accepted by bb_bqueue_create(); sizes
        the static per-instance item storage array. bb_bqueue_create()
        returns BB_ERR_INVALID_ARG if cfg->capacity exceeds this.

        SRAM cost: worst-case static footprint across the whole pool is
        BB_BQUEUE_MAX_INSTANCES * BB_BQUEUE_MAX_CAPACITY *
        BB_BQUEUE_MAX_ITEM_BYTES bytes (default: 2 * 16 * 64 = 2048 bytes),
        reserved regardless of any single instance's actual cfg. Raising
        this to satisfy one caller's large queue costs that extra SRAM for
        EVERY pooled instance, not just that caller's.

config BB_BQUEUE_MAX_ITEM_BYTES
    int "Maximum item size (bytes) per instance"
    default 64
    help
        Upper bound on cfg->item_bytes accepted by bb_bqueue_create(); sizes
        the static per-instance item storage array. bb_bqueue_create()
        returns BB_ERR_INVALID_ARG if cfg->item_bytes exceeds this.

        SRAM cost: worst-case static footprint across the whole pool is
        BB_BQUEUE_MAX_INSTANCES * BB_BQUEUE_MAX_CAPACITY *
        BB_BQUEUE_MAX_ITEM_BYTES bytes (default: 2 * 16 * 64 = 2048 bytes),
        reserved regardless of any single instance's actual cfg. Raising
        this to satisfy one caller's large item type costs that extra SRAM
        for EVERY pooled instance, not just that caller's.

endmenu
